article.description:
Katie Douglas scored a season-high 22 points, and Nykesha Sales added 16 to lead host Connecticut to a
64-51 victory over Los Angeles on Tuesday.
article.headline: Leslie has 20 and 14 in L.A. loss
article.linkText: Douglas' season-high 22 lead Sun past Sparks
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- The Connecticut Sun have Los Angeles'
number this season and are winning virtually every time they play
against the Western Conference.

The Eastern Conference-leading Sun ran their league-best record
to 21-6 Tuesday night with a 64-51 win over the Sparks, to finish
with a 13-1 record over Western Conference opponents. Their only
stumble was a 95-86 loss at Seattle on June 22.

"We've seen teams go west and win this year," Connecticut
coach Mike Thibault said. "You've had a lot of good young players
that come up into the league and into the Eastern Conference.

"There is a lot of good things going on in our conference. I
don't think that there's a big gap anymore."

Katie Douglas scored a season-high 22 points, and Nykesha Sales
added 16 to lead the Connecticut.

Douglas hit a career-high 12 free throws in 14 tries in a
physical game marked by 42 fouls and technicals on Sparks coach
Henry Bibby and center Lisa Leslie.

The Sun have already clinched a playoff spot. The Sparks (12-14)
are trying to stay in the postseason picture. The Sun have swept
both games against the two-time champion Sparks, whom they held to
a season-low in points.

"The trademark of this team the past few years has been our
selflessness," Douglas said. "That was evident tonight. A big
reason why we won the ballgame was that, while sometimes we are not
knocking down the shots, we are making those extra passes."

Connecticut now enters the home stretch of the season with the
emphasis on "home." The Sun are 11-1 at Mohegan Sun arena and
have five of their last seven games at home.

Los Angeles, meanwhile, is 2-5 on an eight-game road trip that
winds up Wednesday night in New York. Bibby said he didn't think
the travel was wearing on his team.

"I think we weren't focused on the basket," he said. "We
played pretty good defense. We couldn't get a call, we couldn't
knock down an open shot and we couldn't make a layup. So it's tough
to win games when you do that."

Leslie led the Sparks with 20 points and 14 rebounds. Her jumper
with just under a minute gone in the game was the Sparks' only
lead.

Both teams had their share of offensive problems in the first
half, shooting a combined 22-of-64. Douglas gave Connecticut an
early cushion, scoring nine of her 10 first-half points in the
first seven minutes for a 13-5 lead.

The Sun led by as many as 10 when Sale's 3-pointer put
Connecticut up 19-9 with 8:22 left.

Los Angeles countered with a 10-2 surge. Leslie added five
points in the spurt to pull the Sparks within three. But Margo
Dydek dumped in a pair of baskets over the next minute, and the Sun
held on down the stretch to hold a 32-24 lead at the break.

Sales hit a pair of 3-pointers to open the second half, and the
Sun were not tested thereafter.

Douglas, who also had eight rebounds, drew the defensive
assignment on Chamique Holdsclaw, and along with reserve forward
Brooke Wyckoff, helped hold her to just 5 points, 13 below her
average.

"(Holdsclaw) is a tough player," Douglas said. "It wasn't
just myself and Brooke. It was all five of us talking, helping and
rotating."

The Sun will be without Dydek for at least the next two games.
The 7-foot-2 center joins her Polish national team this week to
compete in the European Championship qualifier.

"I like how we're playing defense," Thibault said. "We just
went out of rhythm on offense. We've got to try and clean it up,
but we're playing hard enough to win games."
